caption: The food is amazing.  If you're vegetarian there's a lot of yummy stuff.  I suggest the vegan mofongo.  The only criticism is that they don't have takeaway or printed menus.  The menu online is not the same as what's in the restaurant so you can call in an order but you have to already know the menu.  Also if you are vegan the Puerto Rican rice has pork in it.  It tastes great if you're not.  They have a good sized warning but its in the store.  So as you see even with that I gave it five stars.  That's how good the food is.

I visited and ordered a steak jibarito. Now growing up in humboldt park, and being around all of my Puertorican friends and they're families, I've had my fair share of Puertorican food. While the service was great, hence the 3 stars, the food was not what I'd call authentic puertorican food. The arroz con gandules while tasty, seemed like they were lacking sazon, and instead of mashed or minced garlic on the jibarito they used a type of garlic paste. The steak could've been seasoned better as well. I would honestly just stick with one of the more authentic restaurants in Humboldt Park.

It was delicious! The rice was cook on point and had a great taste, not to mention the Mofongo con camarones in the red sauce. Also I have to say the Alcapurrias, rellenos de papas and empanadas were nice and crispy, they were made to the order. Oh, and I almost forgot to mention how good was the pastelillo de guayaba even though they are different from the ones we have in Puerto Rico.  The restaurant is a small place, but the food and the service has the quality of 5 stars. I recommend it and will visit again. Buen provecho!

I called ahead and placed a to go order for the steak and onion platter which came with rice and sweet plantains, also ordered a side of papa majada which is a whipped potato salad which was really good and a side if maduros (sweet plantains). The total came out to a little over $15.00 which was really great given that it was in Chicago and what I was ordering.  I don't think I would go there and try it out again as another menu that I came across had the steak and onion platter that came with peppers and onions. I didn't get that. Wish I would have, but anyways the steak wasn't flavorful at all. The rice just came with pigeon peas as I thought or heard from someone that puertorican rice has a variety of things in it including a variety of peppers. Will pass on this restaurant when in Chicago next time.

Uber eats awesome on delivering food hot. Jibarito were very good. Steak or pork flavorful.  The downer sides of rice and bean pitiful. For an item that cost pennies to make they sure do know how to measure. Beans came out to be about 1 1/2 ounces of actual beans in a nice tiny cup. White rice which is basically boiled in water and oil also measured..  The side sauces which cost extra are served in those tiny thimble containers the places use for ketchup. Since ive been to the actual island more than 10 times i have never seen anyone in puerto rico give serving this small even after the hurricane. If the ladies who run this spot figure it out families will likely start eating at the actual restaurant.   Ladies rice and bean are very economical and fried plantain pull it together. Go by los camales. A block down and count the sauces they give and look at the crowd.

If you're ever craving a DELICIOUS jibarrito, this is the spot you need to go to! The jibarritos here are SO GOOD! The location is right on 18th street & Paulina, down the 18th street strip. So it has a very nice location! The staff seems polite, and alert. I've always been greeted upon arrival. Sometimes it does get busy so I understand the lack of communication / personalization of clerk / customer interaction. I've never left unhappy or disappointed once I leave the restaurant. The location is appropriately sized, it fits a good amount of people. Different table sizes for different party sizes. The food is reasonably priced. Of course, only jibarritos. Different types of jibarrito options like steak, chicken, pork, vegetarian, even vegan! You have 2 size options of servings, either a half or full jibarrito. You also get a choice of cheese on your jibarrito, as well as 2 rice options. Other side options include empanadas, salads, sweet plantains, yucca fries, and avocado to name a few. A few dessert options if you still have room for it once you're done with your meal. Various drinks like Coke, Diet Coke, Sprite, water, and coconut water. Also the location offers a catering menu if you're holding a feast / gathering. Within distance there's also a bakery, ice cream shop, crepe restaurant, Mexican art store, Dunkin Donuts, Bank of America, and the CTA Pink Line. Very neat location, the food is great, and it's in the heart of Pilsen.
